{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17529226","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17529226"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:52:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:52:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14368"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14368","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14368"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.06,0.4,0.11,0.41]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7063"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112735"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7063","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7063"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14368"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94768"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2166"},{"type":"tags","id":"2746"},{"type":"tags","id":"3593"},{"type":"tags","id":"4405"},{"type":"tags","id":"8189"},{"type":"tags","id":"12804"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16839"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18872"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46190"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46294"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112735","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112735"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for antenatal care. She is 12 weeks\u0027 pregnant with her first child. She has a medical history of Graves\u0027 disease diagnosed five years ago, for which she underwent a total thyroidectomy three years ago. She has been on levothyroxine replacement therapy since the surgery. She does not take any other regular medications. On examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Thyroid function tests performed one week ago showed TSH 1.8 mU/L (0.4-4.0) and free T4 16 pmol/L (9-19).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most important investigation to perform at this stage of pregnancy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Thyroid ultrasound","24-hour urinary iodine","TSH receptor antibodies (TRAb)","T3","Repeat thyroid function tests"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, the most important investigation to perform is measuring \u003Cstrong\u003ETSH receptor antibodies (TRAb)\u003C/strong\u003E. Despite having undergone a total thyroidectomy and currently having normal thyroid function tests, this patient still has a risk of her baby developing neonatal thyrotoxicosis. This is because TRAb, which are responsible for the hyperthyroidism in Graves\u0027 disease, can persist in the circulation even after thyroid removal and can cross the placenta, although do gradually tend to decline post-thyroidectomy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeat thyroid function tests\u003C/strong\u003E are not the most crucial investigation at this point, as the patient\u0027s recent results are within normal limits. While monitoring thyroid function throughout pregnancy is important, it does not provide information about the risk of neonatal thyrotoxicosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ethyroid ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E would not be useful in this patient, as she has already undergone a total thyroidectomy. There is no thyroid tissue to evaluate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMeasuring \u003Cstrong\u003E24-hour urinary iodine\u003C/strong\u003E is not particularly relevant in this case. While iodine status is important during pregnancy, it is not the primary concern given the patient\u0027s history of Graves\u0027 disease and the risk of neonatal thyrotoxicosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ET3\u003C/strong\u003E measurement is not necessary at this stage. The patient\u0027s TSH and free T4 are within normal limits, indicating adequate thyroid hormone replacement. T3 levels would not provide additional information about the risk of neonatal thyrotoxicosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMeasuring TRAb is crucial because these antibodies can cross the placenta and stimulate the fetal thyroid gland, potentially causing neonatal thyrotoxicosis. This condition can occur even if the mother\u0027s thyroid function is normal, as the antibodies can persist long after treatment of Graves\u0027 disease. If TRAb levels are elevated, close monitoring of the fetus for signs of thyrotoxicosis (such as tachycardia, growth restriction, or goitre) would be warranted, and the neonate would require careful evaluation after birth. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFrequency of monitoring depends on the clinical situation:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEarly pregnancy for baseline assessment; \u003C/strong\u003Eif negative, further testing is not required unless the mother remains on anti-thyroid drugs\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConsider repeat TRAb testing at 18-20 weeks\u0027 gestation\u003C/strong\u003E if elevated in early pregnancy or for mothers on anti-thyroid drugs in mid-pregnancy\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConsider repeat TRAb testing at 30-34 weeks\u0027 gestation\u003C/strong\u003E if elevated at 18-20 weeks\u0027 gestation or for mothers on anti-thyroid drugs in the third trimester \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe risk of neonatal thyrotoxicosis is most elevated at levels exceeding three-times the upper limit of normal (3X ULN). \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["TSH receptor antibodies (TRAb) can cross the placenta and cause neonatal thyrotoxicosis, even in mothers with treated Graves\u0027 disease.","Monitoring TRAb levels during pregnancy is crucial for assessing the risk of neonatal thyrotoxicosis in women with a history of Graves\u0027 disease.","Normal thyroid function tests in a pregnant woman with treated Graves\u0027 disease do not rule out the risk of neonatal thyrotoxicosis."],"references":["Moss J, Solomon M, Wilson S. Thyroid disease in the perinatal period. Aust Fam Physician. 2012 Aug;41(8):578-81. Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2012/august/thyroid-disease-in-the-perinatal-period","Bucci, I., Giuliani, C. and Napolitano, G. (2017). Thyroid-Stimulating Hormone Receptor Antibodies in Pregnancy: Clinical Relevance. Frontiers in Endocrinology, 8(1). doi:https://doi.org/10.3389/fendo.2017.00137.","Alexander, E.K., Pearce, E.N., Brent, G.A., Brown, R.S., Chen, H., Dosiou, C., Grobman, W.A., Laurberg, P., Lazarus, J.H., Mandel, S.J., Peeters, R.P. and Sullivan, S. (2017). 2017 Guidelines of the American Thyroid Association for the Diagnosis and Management of Thyroid Disease During Pregnancy and the Postpartum. Thyroid, [online] 27(3), pp.315\u2013389. doi:https://doi.org/10.1089/thy.2016.0457."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94768"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14368"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94768","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94768"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-04T13:27:19+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-04T13:28:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7063"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112735"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app